02:01:58,450 --> 02:02:05,413
Is that being shifted over in this budget to kind of reflect for some of the agreements that have been settled since the previous fiscal year budget?

1185
02:02:10,517 --> 02:02:10,777
Thank you.

1186
02:02:10,797 --> 02:02:15,744
Yes, there would be a change, a significant change, because I think historically the number's been over $1 million.

1187
02:02:16,724 --> 02:02:19,625
There's going to be a significant change since we've settled contracts.

1188
02:02:19,645 --> 02:02:21,947
We don't have any open contracts as of right now.

1189
02:02:22,007 --> 02:02:32,072
We are working through negotiations for a contract that will effectively open 7-1, which, you know, another way to say it is that it ends 6-30.

1190
02:02:32,572 --> 02:02:34,773
So yes, there's going to be a significant change in those numbers.

1191
02:02:35,313 --> 02:02:37,094
That's still being finalized too, but yes.

1192
02:02:37,434 --> 02:02:37,634
Sure.

1193
02:02:37,655 --> 02:02:44,358
Yeah, I'm just trying to provide some context because obviously if, and you see in a big budget, difficult budget year and then you come to look at this budget and you see,

1194
02:02:45,210 --> 02:02:53,115
you know, 17% increase in the salary line, you know, that was actually being budgeted for through this contractual agreement section in the past.

1195
02:02:53,415 --> 02:02:53,615
All right.

1196
02:02:53,635 --> 02:02:54,235
Yes, absolutely.

1197
02:02:54,375 --> 02:02:54,655
Thank you.

1198
02:02:55,216 --> 02:02:55,576
Thank you.

1199
02:02:55,696 --> 02:02:55,936
All right.

1200
02:02:56,016 --> 02:02:58,798
I will go to Councilor Boehling and then Vice President Lazaro.

1201
02:03:00,279 --> 02:03:00,999
Thank you very much.

1202
02:03:01,019 --> 02:03:02,180
I just had a question.

1203
02:03:03,601 --> 02:03:12,145
On the weapons apparatus stipend, it looks like it was budgeted for 58 and it's again for 58 but there's no actuals in there.

1204
02:03:12,886 --> 02:03:13,126
Is that?

1205
02:03:14,951 --> 02:03:15,472
We'll say that again?

1206
02:03:15,892 --> 02:03:26,677
For the weapons apparatus stipend that it looks like it was budgeted for 58 and again for 58, 600, I know it's a slight increase, but there's no actuals.

1207
02:03:26,697 --> 02:03:29,038
Does that come in towards the end of the fiscal year?

1208
02:03:30,599 --> 02:03:30,839
Yes.

1209
02:03:31,419 --> 02:03:32,400
That is in June.

1210
02:03:32,940 --> 02:03:33,420
Okay.

1211
02:03:33,540 --> 02:03:39,523
And it's a flat stipend depending on whether it's a superior officer or a patrol officer.

1212
02:03:40,184 --> 02:03:41,464
The amounts are different.

1213
02:03:42,025 --> 02:03:42,305
Okay.

1214
02:03:42,645 --> 02:03:42,845
Great.

1215
02:03:43,640 --> 02:03:50,746
And then I think the other question I had was around the contracts, but I think you all explained that already, so thank you.

1216
02:03:52,268 --> 02:03:52,588
Thank you.

1217
02:03:52,608 --> 02:03:53,529
Vice President Lazaro.

1218
02:03:55,551 --> 02:03:55,991
Thank you.

1219
02:03:56,011 --> 02:04:03,618
I just want to draw attention to the fact that I believe that there was a $2.4 million deficit.

1220
02:04:05,019 --> 02:04:09,023
Madam Chief of Staff, would you mind clarifying for me what the deficit is that

1221
02:04:11,629 --> 02:04:14,896
We keep talking about how much is the deficit for this budget this year?

1222
02:04:22,074 --> 02:04:22,955
That is correct.

1223
02:04:23,135 --> 02:04:25,777
That's just like kind of uncanny.

1224
02:04:26,438 --> 02:04:29,460
It's the exact amount that is that the police budget has gone up.

1225
02:04:29,520 --> 02:04:35,425
So it's interesting that we there was no so like you knew that you guys knew this was coming because the contract was negotiated.

1226
02:04:36,125 --> 02:04:42,830
And then there what we have to cut is the schools and the library and the city council budget and every other department.

1227
02:04:43,451 --> 02:04:50,136
And to pay for the police budget that was contractually negotiated knowingly.

1228
02:04:51,977 --> 02:04:54,919
I mean, can you explain why that happened that way?

1229
02:04:57,581 --> 02:05:04,026
The contractual process is such that the city had been in negotiations.

1230
02:05:04,086 --> 02:05:05,688
I don't know the timelines, to be honest with you.

1231
02:05:05,728 --> 02:05:08,710
These gentlemen would probably know the timelines better than I would.

1232
02:05:09,510 --> 02:05:15,513
The city was going through a contractual negotiation with both the patrol union and the superiors union.

1233
02:05:17,674 --> 02:05:24,158
As a part of that process, the unions have the option to file with the joint labor management committee.

1234
02:05:24,918 --> 02:05:27,960
The joint management labor committee is a mandated

1235
02:05:30,780 --> 02:05:36,582
essentially mediation and an arbitration process that is, you know, established and codified in mass general law.

1236
02:05:37,543 --> 02:05:43,265
And both police and fire can file with the Joint Labor Management Committee.

1237
02:05:43,945 --> 02:05:45,806
And it's a mandated process.

1238
02:05:45,846 --> 02:05:52,548
We can't elect to not negotiate or we can't elect to get to an impasse.

1239
02:05:52,628 --> 02:05:54,469
We must follow the process.

1240
02:05:55,449 --> 02:06:17,519
I can't, I don't recall exactly all the stages, but just before some of the final, we were actually in the final process towards getting a decision awarded by the JLMC before the union was able to settle and the city was able to settle with the union.

1241
02:06:17,539 --> 02:06:18,839
So you were like at an impasse?

1242
02:06:19,620 --> 02:06:19,840
Sorry?

1243
02:06:19,980 --> 02:06:22,661
You were at an impasse and there was somebody was deciding

1244
02:06:23,987 --> 02:06:29,129
Well, it's such that cities and towns can't get to an impasse, basically.

1245
02:06:29,149 --> 02:06:36,911
The process kind of takes over and it requires cities and towns to... So somebody decided on this contract for you?

1246
02:06:37,111 --> 02:06:38,091
No.

1247
02:06:39,092 --> 02:06:45,053
So through the process, we were doing extensive amounts of research and work.

1248
02:06:45,494 --> 02:06:52,876
I actually have a binder somewhere that we put together for the process, for the negotiations to ensure that

1249
02:06:53,476 --> 02:07:00,158
We had gone through our due diligence and looked around the Commonwealth, looked at other cities and towns to understand what numbers they were settling at.

1250
02:07:01,299 --> 02:07:11,042
It's important for us to make sure that we tell the city's story in terms of the city's available dollars and budget in that process.

1251
02:07:13,423 --> 02:07:18,904
We essentially present at that arbitration hearing and we present information to.

1252
02:07:18,924 --> 02:07:19,564
Okay.

1253
02:07:19,584 --> 02:07:19,924
We don't have.

1254
02:07:19,944 --> 02:07:20,444
That's okay.

1255
02:07:20,504 --> 02:07:20,844
That's okay.

1256
02:07:21,144 --> 02:07:21,524
I'm sorry.

1257
02:07:21,604 --> 02:07:23,145
We can't keep doing this all night.

1258
02:07:23,565 --> 02:07:26,045
We, what's your lowest paid police officer paid?

1259
02:07:29,486 --> 02:07:31,746
Lowest paid, like entry level.

1260
02:07:31,806 --> 02:07:32,026
Yeah.

1261
02:07:32,066 --> 02:07:32,526
Entry level.

1262
02:07:32,566 --> 02:07:33,807
First step police officer.

1263
02:07:33,907 --> 02:07:34,167
Yeah.

1264
02:07:34,187 --> 02:07:34,167
66,000.

1265
02:07:34,207 --> 02:07:35,407
A year.

1266
02:07:35,447 --> 02:07:35,727
Yeah.

1267
02:07:36,307 --> 02:07:41,768
So if we were to divide that up by hour, how many hours do police officers work per week?

1268
02:07:43,822 --> 02:07:44,383
40 hours a week.

1269
02:07:44,863 --> 02:07:48,767
So I just want to do a quick math, 66.

1270
02:07:48,867 --> 02:07:49,188
Sorry.

1271
02:07:57,788 --> 02:08:03,512
42 divided by 40 is, so that's like $31 an hour.

1272
02:08:03,532 --> 02:08:06,575
$31.70 an hour.

1273
02:08:08,676 --> 02:08:10,317
And that's like a starting level.

1274
02:08:10,958 --> 02:08:14,160
Yeah, because that's a five year step process.

1275
02:08:14,460 --> 02:08:14,660
Yeah.

1276
02:08:16,021 --> 02:08:21,165
And librarians who work in Medford part time, not in the union.

1277
02:08:22,257 --> 02:08:24,978
with a master's degree make $20 an hour.

1278
02:08:25,858 --> 02:08:31,921
So the library is asking for $20,000 to pay them slightly more.

1279
02:08:32,761 --> 02:08:39,543
They still will not be at market rate, but I just want to compare that.

1280
02:08:40,984 --> 02:08:44,205
Were you asked by the chief of staff or the mayor to cut your budget at all?

1281
02:08:46,386 --> 02:08:49,607
After this budget was presented to the mayor's office, were you asked to cut it?

1282
02:08:51,294 --> 02:08:52,895
There were a few cuts made.

1283
02:08:53,195 --> 02:08:54,155
Can you tell me where?

1284
02:08:57,456 --> 02:08:57,977
Overtime.

1285
02:09:02,218 --> 02:09:03,158
In which?

1286
02:09:03,259 --> 02:09:04,559
There are a lot of overtimes.

1287
02:09:04,659 --> 02:09:05,579
Do you remember which one?

1288
02:09:08,280 --> 02:09:10,241
Overtime for officers, clerical, and training.

1289
02:09:10,701 --> 02:09:11,642
All of them?

1290
02:09:12,142 --> 02:09:12,422
Okay.

1291
02:09:13,142 --> 02:09:14,923
And those increases were more based on

1292
02:09:15,999 --> 02:09:16,399
Actuals.

1293
02:09:16,439 --> 02:09:19,360
You know, the actuals and salary increases, so.

1294
02:09:19,720 --> 02:09:19,900
Yeah.

1295
02:09:20,480 --> 02:09:27,002
It's something that also takes part as, you know, how many police officers we're going to have graduating.

1296
02:09:27,402 --> 02:09:28,042
Yeah.

1297
02:09:28,082 --> 02:09:32,223
How many we hire, and it works hand in hand with the overtime, so.

1298
02:09:32,504 --> 02:09:39,906
Another thing I want to ask about is the full-time police officers, the number of positions.

1299
02:09:42,348 --> 02:09:48,091
It looks like you will be planning to hire more patrol officers next year?

1300
02:09:48,131 --> 02:09:50,152
Yes, we currently have 97 right now.

1301
02:09:50,172 --> 02:09:54,855
105 would give us the opportunity to hire another eight right now immediately.

1302
02:09:55,735 --> 02:09:58,317
So eight more patrol officers immediately.

1303
02:09:58,617 --> 02:09:59,057
That's great.

1304
02:10:00,298 --> 02:10:01,278
The fire department.

1305
02:10:03,400 --> 02:10:07,562
Does anybody remember what the fire department was allotted for hiring more firefighters?

1306
02:10:07,622 --> 02:10:08,142
I can't remember.

1307
02:10:08,162 --> 02:10:09,203
I don't think it was.

1308
02:10:11,447 --> 02:10:12,689
It was around 6 or 8.

1309
02:10:12,769 --> 02:10:13,350
I'm not 100% sure.

1310
02:10:21,035 --> 02:10:24,017
Understand how contractual obligations work.

1311
02:10:24,097 --> 02:10:25,738
I know that it took a long time to get there.

1312
02:10:26,278 --> 02:10:36,485
An argument was just made by the mayor tonight that if the lowest paid librarians got an increase in their pay, it would be too much of a jump all at once and it wouldn't be fair to other departments.

1313
02:10:37,045 --> 02:10:46,632
I think this is a great example of what happens when somebody in one department is being right-sized to a contract that might be something that is

1314
02:10:47,793 --> 02:10:50,656
overdue and necessary, perhaps.

1315
02:10:51,998 --> 02:11:04,693
But I don't think you can make the argument that one department in the city

1316
02:11:08,147 --> 02:11:18,652
should have people that get paid a living wage, and another department in the city should have people that just do it for the love of it when everybody needs to eat and prevent for their families.

1317
02:11:19,212 --> 02:11:20,312
And I'm not saying you guys don't.

1318
02:11:20,593 --> 02:11:29,136
I'm just saying that this is a great example of disparity within the same employment unit.

1319
02:11:29,296 --> 02:11:35,379
So I feel frustrated about, I know it's a very big department.

1320
02:11:35,399 --> 02:11:37,200
The police department's very big.

1321
02:11:37,813 --> 02:11:38,975
I understand that.

1322
02:11:39,135 --> 02:11:50,135
But knowing how many times we've heard about the size of the deficit for this year and seeing that it's exactly this increase and that

1323
02:11:52,475 --> 02:11:59,780
All the other departments have just small, small, small asks and that it would make a huge difference for a couple of people.

1324
02:12:01,661 --> 02:12:03,082
I feel frustrated again.

1325
02:12:03,262 --> 02:12:06,264
I do appreciate your responses to that stuff.

1326
02:12:06,324 --> 02:12:08,845
I mean, everything is, it's not unreasonable.

1327
02:12:08,885 --> 02:12:10,747
It's just all very stark.

1328
02:12:11,822 --> 02:12:16,083
And just to clarify the years of the contract, I mean the 2027 fiscal raise for police is 2.5%.

1329
02:12:16,143 --> 02:12:18,524
Yeah, totally.

1330
02:12:19,044 --> 02:12:19,345
Of course.

1331
02:12:19,405 --> 02:12:20,625
It's just that it's been building.

1332
02:12:20,705 --> 02:12:21,425
Yes, of course.

1333
02:12:21,545 --> 02:12:22,065
And I understand.

1334
02:12:22,225 --> 02:12:22,726
I understand that.

1335
02:12:23,646 --> 02:12:27,847
And that is the same thing in the library, too, is that they've been underpaid for so long.

1336
02:12:30,794 --> 02:12:40,477
when the ask was small because the hope was to get maybe if we ask for just a little bit we'll get that and then you got half of that, you know, over and over again for years.

1337
02:12:41,278 --> 02:12:54,942
And I think we just need to think more along the lines of ask for what we deserve now and maybe get a little bit less than like, you know, ask for nothing and get less than that.

1338
02:12:58,260 --> 02:13:09,027
And also that like maybe we have a responsibility as a city to give the people that work here what they deserve all the time, not just every four years and not every 10 years.

1339
02:13:11,229 --> 02:13:11,669
But thank you.

1340
02:13:11,869 --> 02:13:12,449
And I'm sorry.

1341
02:13:12,469 --> 02:13:12,950
Thank you.

1342
02:13:13,670 --> 02:13:13,910
Thanks.

1343
02:13:14,030 --> 02:13:14,291
Thank you.

1344
02:13:16,452 --> 02:13:16,992
Thank you.

1345
02:13:17,012 --> 02:13:19,414
Councillor Callahan.

1346
02:13:20,623 --> 02:13:21,203
Thanks.

1347
02:13:22,004 --> 02:13:23,885
My main questions are just about overtime.

1348
02:13:24,845 --> 02:13:30,368
And also overtime, same as the increase to salaries, overtime also comes to about $2 million.

1349
02:13:31,849 --> 02:13:46,257
And my question about overtime is really, and we asked the fire department about this, and it was a really interesting answer to sort of understand exactly how fire departments are required to have 24, 23 people per shift by law.

1350
02:13:46,437 --> 02:13:48,398
And that means that if they're understaffed,

1351
02:13:49,118 --> 02:13:52,599
They literally have to do overtime and people don't want to do it.

1352
02:13:52,779 --> 02:13:54,159
So it was a very interesting conversation.

1353
02:13:55,619 --> 02:14:00,780
And I would love to understand more about overtime generally in the police department.

1354
02:14:01,500 --> 02:14:14,263
And then if you can, also talk about overtime for things like the crossing guards, like when a crossing guard is missing and then a policeman does that.

1355
02:14:15,583 --> 02:14:19,345
just to understand how much overtime, what is overtime for?

1356
02:14:19,385 --> 02:14:22,146
Why is overtime necessary?

1357
02:14:22,166 --> 02:14:24,187
Why does the police force use overtime?

1358
02:14:24,207 --> 02:14:26,928
I'd love to have a general understanding.

1359
02:14:28,937 --> 02:14:30,658
going to start with the traffic supervisors.

1360
02:14:31,318 --> 02:14:34,880
We don't pay police officers to fill their spots on overtime.

1361
02:14:34,980 --> 02:14:36,341
It's someone comes off the shift.

1362
02:14:36,621 --> 02:14:39,222
It's an hour in the morning, an hour in the afternoon.

1363
02:14:39,682 --> 02:14:43,724
So we work with less people at that time is what happens.

1364
02:14:43,744 --> 02:14:44,565
So it's not overtime.

1365
02:14:44,645 --> 02:14:45,805
So that is not overtime.

1366
02:14:45,845 --> 02:14:46,365
Thank you.

1367
02:14:46,386 --> 02:14:47,206
That's good to know.

1368
02:14:49,912 --> 02:14:58,918
We have a certain amount of people we staff daily, per shift, and we will allow that to go down to a certain number before we have overtime.

1369
02:15:00,980 --> 02:15:03,762
We are often forcing people to stay for overtime.

1370
02:15:05,063 --> 02:15:12,348
It is a large number because the number we have, 97 people, is very, very low.

1371
02:15:12,368 --> 02:15:16,791
I was here, I've been here for 40 years, and I remember when we had 132 offices.

1372
02:15:19,265 --> 02:15:25,306
We probably ran an average of 120 to 25 for a very long time.

1373
02:15:25,486 --> 02:15:29,267
And in the last 10 years, the numbers just kept going down and down and down.

1374
02:15:29,687 --> 02:15:32,308
So the money is one issue.

1375
02:15:32,668 --> 02:15:36,829
There's also an issue with hiring people who people just don't want to do this job.

1376
02:15:37,949 --> 02:15:39,709
And it's become very difficult.

1377
02:15:39,769 --> 02:15:40,750
They're under a lot of stress.

1378
02:15:40,910 --> 02:15:43,750
And therefore, the overtime goes up.

1379
02:15:43,970 --> 02:15:46,031
So instead of having, we're trying to get to 105.

1380
02:15:47,675 --> 02:15:53,217
We're still nowhere near where we should be to service this city, especially a city of this size.

1381
02:15:54,218 --> 02:15:58,539
But if we can get to that, it helps reduce the overtime part a little bit.

1382
02:15:58,859 --> 02:16:01,340
Do you mind if I just ask a little bit more detail?

1383
02:16:01,360 --> 02:16:01,660
Sure.

1384
02:16:02,221 --> 02:16:10,324
My understanding from the fire department is that there's a legal requirement per fire truck or per station.

1385
02:16:10,564 --> 02:16:12,885
There are standards, industry standards to maintain.

1386
02:16:13,445 --> 02:16:21,947
So I would love to, like, how does the police department determine if overtime, if overtime is guesstimated?

1387
02:16:21,967 --> 02:16:22,587
We have numbers.

1388
02:16:22,607 --> 02:16:25,148
Like, how are those numbers determined?

1389
02:16:25,208 --> 02:16:27,588
We have four sectors in the city.

1390
02:16:28,048 --> 02:16:29,889
Each sector has two officers.

1391
02:16:30,369 --> 02:16:32,950
That's an average of eight officers per sector.

1392
02:16:33,310 --> 02:16:34,910
There'll be two sergeants in the street.

1393
02:16:35,150 --> 02:16:36,911
One is the east side, one is the west side.

1394
02:16:37,351 --> 02:16:38,531
So you're talking 10 there.

1395
02:16:38,951 --> 02:16:40,471
Sergeant staffing is a little different.

1396
02:16:40,931 --> 02:16:42,752
But we'll go down as low as six.

1397
02:16:43,552 --> 02:16:48,393
We won't go lower than six unless we just can't get personnel to fill.

1398
02:16:49,573 --> 02:16:50,813
But six is low.

1399
02:16:50,993 --> 02:16:54,534
That's a low number to be running around there, whether it's a daytime or evening or midnights.

1400
02:16:54,974 --> 02:16:55,634
But we do it.

1401
02:16:55,894 --> 02:16:59,675
And one catastrophic event can just put us behind.

1402
02:16:59,715 --> 02:17:03,356
We're fortunate that we have several cities and towns that step up and help.

1403
02:17:03,396 --> 02:17:04,316
They're all in the same boat.

1404
02:17:04,856 --> 02:17:07,597
So mutual aid is a big thing in our business right now.

1405
02:17:09,437 --> 02:17:11,778
So that's the number.

1406
02:17:12,379 --> 02:17:26,626
A full staff would be the eight sector cars, two to four motorcycles, depending on the shift, a K-9 officer, which we do have another K-9 officer, who's often bumped into the sector cars.

1407
02:17:26,947 --> 02:17:29,848
So he's not out doing his regular K-9 routine.

1408
02:17:29,868 --> 02:17:30,729
He has to answer calls.

1409
02:17:31,109 --> 02:17:34,991
And then when we need a K-9 specifically, we'll take him out of that sector.

1410
02:17:37,532 --> 02:17:43,896
We have detectives, we're down to, it's a bare minimum detectives unit following up on cases.

1411
02:17:44,316 --> 02:17:48,818
We often get complaints from people that feel we should be following up on their case.

1412
02:17:49,199 --> 02:18:05,407
When I was a detective lieutenant, I had explained to them that based on the situation that they're in and the lack of solvability factors, their case got put aside and other cases are assigned to people because we just don't have enough people to take on every case that they want.

1413
02:18:06,528 --> 02:18:08,309
our citizens want us to follow up on.

1414
02:18:08,469 --> 02:18:13,292
When you become a victim, in some circumstance, you know, we feel for you.

1415
02:18:13,592 --> 02:18:15,313
We don't want you to be stuck out there.

1416
02:18:15,333 --> 02:18:23,038
But there are some cases that just don't, they don't have the solvability factors and the level of the crime really isn't

1417
02:18:24,360 --> 02:18:26,160
I hate to say isn't high, but it isn't.

1418
02:18:26,680 --> 02:18:29,801
And so we have to put that on the back burner.

1419
02:18:30,401 --> 02:18:36,323
When the detectives are, you know, when things might slow down a little bit, they'll pick at those cases and try to resolve them.

1420
02:18:36,383 --> 02:18:44,464
But I've seen our numbers, like I said, go from 132 down to 97 right now.

1421
02:18:44,904 --> 02:18:46,465
I've seen them go as low as 90.

1422
02:18:48,185 --> 02:18:50,726
And we usually would be bouncing back up within a couple of years.

1423
02:18:50,866 --> 02:18:52,406
We're not seeing that bounce back up now.

1424
02:18:53,026 --> 02:18:58,057
It's been five years now, so it's at least more than five years that our numbers have been dropping.

1425
02:19:00,528 --> 02:19:02,329
It's difficult to get people to do this job now.

1426
02:19:04,291 --> 02:19:07,413
Also, it's a six-month training academy.

1427
02:19:08,533 --> 02:19:09,974
We talk about a master's degree.

1428
02:19:10,034 --> 02:19:15,098
It's certainly not a master's degree, but the amount of credits that would be built into it would give you an associate's degree.

1429
02:19:16,198 --> 02:19:25,744
You may be making the same amount of money when you come out as the person who's hired to say work for the DPW that's sweeping the ground, but you are now

1430
02:19:27,625 --> 02:19:45,510
You have specialized in mass criminal laws, mass traffic laws, motor vehicle laws, working with people in domestic violence, working with people in mental health issues, as well as all the defensive tactics and firearms things that we go through.

1431
02:19:45,870 --> 02:19:49,611
So there's a lot of work that goes to it, and their pay is not good when they're in there.

1432
02:19:49,931 --> 02:19:54,813
So some people will leave a career because they want to be a police officer, and they'll sacrifice that.

1433
02:19:55,393 --> 02:19:57,014
pay to commit.

1434
02:19:57,074 --> 02:20:02,379
And then after they get out of the academy, they'll get up to that step one pay that we just talked about.

1435
02:20:02,799 --> 02:20:08,164
So we're all suffering to get somewhere.

1436
02:20:08,364 --> 02:20:14,149
And unfortunately, and I understand your comparison, your goal is to get everybody a pay raise.

1437
02:20:15,990 --> 02:20:19,333
The unfortunate thing is I know that the

1438
02:20:19,923 --> 02:20:23,485
Librarian may have a master's degree, but so do most police officers right now.

1439
02:20:23,965 --> 02:20:24,465
I have one.

1440
02:20:25,025 --> 02:20:25,706
I know he does.

1441
02:20:26,026 --> 02:20:27,406
And those guys over there do.

1442
02:20:27,746 --> 02:20:31,028
So many of them officers do have bachelor's degrees, too.

1443
02:20:31,328 --> 02:20:36,630
So there might be a couple that don't have a college degree, but most people are working towards it.

1444
02:20:37,771 --> 02:20:43,073
So there is that educational aspect that we carry on on our own.

1445
02:20:44,614 --> 02:20:49,436
And there's also that you go to work as in the library, odds are you're going home that night.

1446
02:20:49,996 --> 02:20:52,057
In this job, you never know how you're going to end up.

1447
02:20:52,277 --> 02:20:54,679
We had an event this morning that an officer was almost killed.

1448
02:20:55,339 --> 02:21:03,804
And so that risk is also a deciding factor on not just your educational background, but what are the things you're willing to do to help the public.

1449
02:21:04,084 --> 02:21:06,305
So thank you.

1450
02:21:06,705 --> 02:21:06,945
Thanks.

1451
02:21:07,506 --> 02:21:10,207
As far as overtime is concerned, I'd like to elaborate on one more thing.

1452
02:21:10,567 --> 02:21:15,030
Back to your question, too, is when I say 97, I should have probably said

1453
02:21:15,810 --> 02:21:20,892
We have 91, like, because six, 91 are actually sworn.

1454
02:21:21,372 --> 02:21:23,112
We have six in the academy right now.

1455
02:21:23,132 --> 02:21:24,993
We have two graduating very soon.

1456
02:21:26,233 --> 02:21:31,635
And that's part of that 97 number I probably should have elaborated on earlier.

1457
02:21:31,895 --> 02:21:32,355
That's helpful.

1458
02:21:36,056 --> 02:21:36,216
Thanks.

