I didn't do that.

1469
02:22:01,369 --> 02:22:02,009
So I'm in trouble here.

1470
02:22:02,069 --> 02:22:07,112
But I did notice that it is split up into like officers, clerical, and training.

1471
02:22:07,192 --> 02:22:11,194
Is there anything that would be interesting for us to know about what is training overtime?

1472
02:22:11,274 --> 02:22:14,416
Why is there overtime for training and clerical?

1473
02:22:14,436 --> 02:22:15,517
How are those different from each other?

1474
02:22:16,218 --> 02:22:21,561
Oftentimes we send people to training on their days off, because our schedule's not a regular Monday through Friday schedule.

1475
02:22:21,981 --> 02:22:24,002
So we have to pay them overtime, it's a contractual thing.

1476
02:22:24,503 --> 02:22:29,586
Or if we send them in lieu of their shift, we often have to fill that spot with an overtime shift.

1477
02:22:29,626 --> 02:22:30,586
So that's what that's for.

1478
02:22:30,606 --> 02:22:30,906
Great, thanks.

1479
02:22:35,989 --> 02:22:42,653
And to your statement, which is true about building up the money over the years.

1480
02:22:43,815 --> 02:22:46,778
I can remember when I came on, the pay was $20,000 a year.

1481
02:22:46,798 --> 02:22:50,242
So it's a building process.

1482
02:22:50,262 --> 02:22:54,086
And I don't think 66 is probably the equivalent of $20,000 a year.

1483
02:23:00,492 --> 02:23:02,954
And police officer training is worth, is more than $150,000.

1484
02:23:03,134 --> 02:23:05,935
I mean, we get it from a lot of different funding sources.

1485
02:23:06,796 --> 02:23:10,358
So that's, we get it from multiple funding sources.

1486
02:23:10,418 --> 02:23:13,980
So that's just from our budget side of it.

1487
02:23:14,120 --> 02:23:14,961
There's more training than $150,000.

1488
02:23:18,362 --> 02:23:19,263
Just to clarify that.

1489
02:23:19,923 --> 02:23:22,165
Over the years, we've established our own training program.

1490
02:23:22,185 --> 02:23:28,208
The industry has established training programs whether we participate or not is the department's thing.

1491
02:23:28,228 --> 02:23:32,931
But as the state grew, as we grew, the state came up with mandates and laws.

1492
02:23:33,391 --> 02:23:39,815
Now, we have the post commission which has increased our normal training by more and they're mandated.

1493
02:23:39,935 --> 02:23:41,276
So, that cost is still going.

1494
02:23:41,336 --> 02:23:42,017
It goes up even more.

1495
02:23:44,058 --> 02:23:44,418
Thank you.

1496
02:23:44,658 --> 02:23:47,340
Oh, sorry, Vice President Lazaro.

1497
02:23:48,734 --> 02:23:56,600
I just wanted to clarify quickly, I didn't intend for my comment to be that it's a comparison of education or that.

1498
02:23:58,916 --> 02:24:02,918
having or not having a certain degree means that you deserve more or less money.

1499
02:24:02,958 --> 02:24:23,109
I just mean that if you require somebody to have a degree and then offer them $20 an hour to perform a job, it's often having higher degrees means you may have personal debt, you may have

1500
02:24:23,932 --> 02:24:28,436
a family to provide for, and that was the reason.

1501
02:24:30,531 --> 02:24:35,054
And usually it implies, like, you would have higher pay, hopefully.

1502
02:24:35,435 --> 02:24:37,056
But that's all I meant.

1503
02:24:37,076 --> 02:24:46,062
It wasn't that, like, I just wanted to compare, like, an entry level position with something that would be maybe a step beyond entry level, because they would have had more training and education.

1504
02:24:47,183 --> 02:24:50,045
Not to say it's apples to apples, because it's not.

1505
02:24:50,145 --> 02:24:56,149
It's just that when we're looking at different departments' budgets, and we're talking about,

1506
02:24:58,482 --> 02:25:00,743
how much money is really at stake.

1507
02:25:02,123 --> 02:25:09,544
And it's really hard to compare across departments, because the police department is so big, and then when we're going to talk about the school budget, and it's also huge.

1508
02:25:10,804 --> 02:25:18,446
And it's just, it's really hard to do this, and that's why it's useful to have these conversations, but I do appreciate the perspective you share as well.

1509
02:25:19,386 --> 02:25:26,027
And I think that everybody should be able to come into a position, in an entry level position, it used to be true in a lot more,

1510
02:25:27,027 --> 02:25:32,974
careers that you can come in with a salary that you can live on.

1511
02:25:33,996 --> 02:25:37,420
I think that should be kind of baseline for most places, and it's really not.

1512
02:25:38,621 --> 02:25:39,983
That's why people live with their parents for longer.

1513
02:25:40,023 --> 02:25:41,805
That's why, like, you know, they rely on each other.

1514
02:25:41,865 --> 02:25:42,886
They have roommates, that kind of thing.

1515
02:25:43,327 --> 02:25:45,569
But anyway, I appreciate this moment.

1516
02:25:45,770 --> 02:25:45,950
Thanks.

1517
02:25:48,878 --> 02:25:49,258
Thank you.

