03:18:42,082 --> 03:18:49,667
I also wanted to say that, as you know, we've been, Medford Public Schools is going through some changes in leadership.

2050
03:18:50,488 --> 03:19:01,155
And we've brought on, in a new superintendent for curriculum and instruction, and well, academics and instruction, our chief operations officer, and so with.

2051
03:19:02,497 --> 03:19:03,498
shifts like that.

2052
03:19:03,518 --> 03:19:08,061
A lot of the work, too, that has happened this year is a review.

2053
03:19:08,761 --> 03:19:10,523
It's a review of how we've done things.

2054
03:19:10,583 --> 03:19:13,945
It's a review of what we want for our students.

2055
03:19:14,666 --> 03:19:24,593
And even some of that conversation and that visioning work is also part of the work we're doing that goes into the MSBA for the high school project.

2056
03:19:25,353 --> 03:19:31,598
So Jerry and Noel can speak a little bit to some of the things that we've been talking about.

2057
03:19:31,658 --> 03:19:40,365
In that first presentation, it, we have always been asked for transparency from school committee.

2058
03:19:40,866 --> 03:19:47,491
So a lot of the work that we were doing initially was, how do we want, how do we envision Medford Public Schools to be running?

2059
03:19:48,192 --> 03:19:49,393
And a lot of that was

2060
03:19:50,578 --> 03:19:55,201
increases in professional development for teachers.

2061
03:19:57,102 --> 03:20:01,124
Jerry mentioned at school committee about what the percentage is, it's 1%.

2062
03:20:02,665 --> 03:20:12,010
I believe of a district's budget should be or that's maybe it's average calculation to be applied and we are like woefully under that 1%.

2063
03:20:13,571 --> 03:20:34,751
So that's just one area where we've really had to look at maybe grant funding or supplemental funding or just creativity within house and kind of look to see what are the priorities for professional development this year, what can we be creative with, what can we use for grant funding or things like that.

2064
03:20:37,780 --> 03:20:48,792
There may there are also conversations around just structure and what we're giving to our school leaders and our department leaders.

2065
03:20:49,893 --> 03:20:50,955
The number one.

2066
03:20:51,938 --> 03:20:58,401
thing that we are guided by all the time is making sure, and Noel spoke to this at the beginning, it's students first.

2067
03:20:59,281 --> 03:21:04,504
So it's what can we do to have decisions be farthest away from students?

2068
03:21:05,244 --> 03:21:06,945
And so that is staffing.

2069
03:21:07,205 --> 03:21:10,406
So what are the other things that we can look at?

2070
03:21:12,327 --> 03:21:17,111
that is not going to impact students' experience in Medford Public Schools.

2071
03:21:18,912 --> 03:21:24,076
But I would say that that might not necessarily be wholly fair to our staff experiences.

2072
03:21:25,016 --> 03:21:33,002
And a lot of the work in which we want to do to, to get to the Medford Public Schools that we feel the community deserves.

2073
03:21:33,983 --> 03:21:36,725
And then I'll, I'll let Noel and, and Jerry kind of.

2074
03:21:39,889 --> 03:21:40,810
Thank you for that question.

2075
03:21:41,250 --> 03:21:45,893
As the superintendent alluded to, the last thing we ever want to impact is our students in our classroom.

2076
03:21:47,694 --> 03:21:53,798
Some areas, as we talked about, you know, just to talk about new proposal spendings, we'd always start there.

2077
03:21:53,838 --> 03:21:58,121
So new proposal spendings are when we meet with directors, when we meet with principals,

2078
03:21:59,742 --> 03:22:06,970
They come to us with what their base budget was last year, and then they say, here are some increases I would like to make, and here's why, and they identify areas.

2079
03:22:07,630 --> 03:22:18,702
One area the superintendent alluded to that we really want to fund, not that it's professional development, really trying to invest in getting really good professional development.

2080
03:22:20,143 --> 03:22:27,027
For our teachers, purchasing and looking at new curriculum if we're hoping to not have to postpone that.

2081
03:22:27,667 --> 03:22:36,313
Also, as Jerry alluded to, we had a great assessment last year on all of our schools for facilities.

2082
03:22:37,293 --> 03:22:41,737
There are some projects that I know Ken Lord would love to get off the ground that I know we would love to fund.

2083
03:22:41,817 --> 03:22:56,408
And we would not just have to go to free cash, but also just put it in our operating budget so that we can consistently invest in our buildings and grounds, consistently invest in our building repairs for the HVAC systems, for our elevators.

2084
03:22:56,428 --> 03:22:58,870
So those are areas that sadly we would have to look at and see.

2085
03:23:00,071 --> 03:23:05,996
If you think of it as like a code, you've got your code red, which is our most important things, and you've got your code orange,

2086
03:23:06,430 --> 03:23:08,130
your code yellow, and then your code green.

2087
03:23:08,710 --> 03:23:20,832
And we would, for facilities purposes, without speaking for our COO, we would look at our code reds and our code oranges, and then have to look at our code yellows and say, hey, I know some of those code yellows you really wanted to get done.

2088
03:23:21,573 --> 03:23:30,334
We might have to either come back to the city council later in the next fiscal year for some free cash, or we might look to postpone that to fiscal year 28.

2089
03:23:30,934 --> 03:23:33,275
Similar with some of the curriculum, I know that,

2090
03:23:35,875 --> 03:23:44,542
Dr. Talbot is doing a fantastic job in reviewing how we are running the district as a whole and reviewing our curriculum.

2091
03:23:44,582 --> 03:23:52,349
So I know she's identifying some areas she would love to see more instructional, more hands-on instructional supplies.

2092
03:23:53,089 --> 03:23:54,290
to go with the curriculum.

2093
03:23:54,810 --> 03:24:01,735
Again, not that we want to postpone that, but that might be something where we wanted to say we wanted to invest $75,000 in our science department.

2094
03:24:02,295 --> 03:24:06,197
We might be only able to invest $50,000 where every department may have to take a small hit.

2095
03:24:06,237 --> 03:24:10,480
Again, I'm just throwing up numbers based on preliminary conversations we have.

2096
03:24:11,040 --> 03:24:13,022
These are never easy conversations to have.

2097
03:24:13,462 --> 03:24:14,382
These are conversations

2098
03:24:15,403 --> 03:24:23,908
we as a district don't want to have, but we are well aware, you know, we're also not going to disrespect any number.

2099
03:24:24,828 --> 03:24:31,832
As we told the mayor beforehand, whatever number we are given, we're going to fit into that number, because at the end of the day, we understand we're a city.

2100
03:24:33,613 --> 03:24:36,756
It's not just the school department, there's the police department, there's DPW department.

2101
03:24:36,776 --> 03:24:39,839
So we don't want to take resources away from every department.

2102
03:24:39,859 --> 03:24:43,142
We also want to make sure that we're doing the best with the funding we have.

2103
03:24:43,462 --> 03:24:50,208
And again, any decisions in which we have to back off of, I don't want to say it's on the chopping block, it might just be

2104
03:24:50,628 --> 03:24:53,089
hey, maybe not now, we might have to look at fiscal year 28.

2105
03:24:53,629 --> 03:25:01,352
But again, every decision we make will always, I can assure you, will always be the furthest from impacting our students in the classroom.

2106
03:25:01,472 --> 03:25:07,635
And as the superintendent alluded to, sometimes that means affecting other staff in other areas that are not in the classroom.

2107
03:25:08,816 --> 03:25:16,663
You know, and so it's a tough, it's still a tough conversation to have, but we do have, we always have a plan B and a plan C ready.

2108
03:25:16,983 --> 03:25:24,910
So those are some of the areas I hope that answered you, your question of like, you know, where we're looking to trim back on and maybe come back in fiscal year 2018.

2109
03:25:25,210 --> 03:25:26,591
You might see that again on the same doc.

2110
03:25:26,631 --> 03:25:29,033
I'll be honest with you, you're gonna see it again on next year's presentation.

2111
03:25:29,654 --> 03:25:32,176
Certain things we didn't get, you're gonna see it right back on there because

2112
03:25:32,676 --> 03:25:42,442
We're gonna continue to advocate for it, and we're gonna continue to fight for it, to continue to provide the best public school, I believe, in the state of Massachusetts when it's all said and done.

2113
03:25:42,962 --> 03:25:43,842
Yeah, no, thank you.

2114
03:25:43,922 --> 03:25:45,883
That very much answers my question.

2115
03:25:45,983 --> 03:25:59,231
I think it's helpful for us to get, I think, a really tangible view of what's at stake and how that impacts our kids, our parents, our teachers.

2116
03:25:59,958 --> 03:26:02,180
their work experience in the schools as well.

2117
03:26:03,561 --> 03:26:07,163
And I think, you know, I think we all have the same goal here, right?

2118
03:26:07,583 --> 03:26:10,285
Of making Medford Public Schools the best school in the state.

2119
03:26:10,325 --> 03:26:11,246
And to

2120
03:26:13,415 --> 03:26:16,658
minimize the effect of any of this on the kids.

2121
03:26:16,698 --> 03:26:19,400
And I think it's really apparent that that's the goal here.

2122
03:26:20,581 --> 03:26:24,484
I think it's also apparent that no matter what we do, it's gonna have an impact.

2123
03:26:25,785 --> 03:26:33,771
And I think that's why our council has, I think, always found it really important to push for the full ask.

2124
03:26:34,872 --> 03:26:37,194
And hopefully this year we can push for that again.

2125
03:26:39,514 --> 03:26:59,891
I'd also like to take a moment to thank our legislative delegation who was able to secure funding in the state budget supplemental for van for the vocational program and for robotics curriculum at the middle school along with,

2126
03:27:02,513 --> 03:27:04,535
equipment to go along with that curriculum.

2127
03:27:04,615 --> 03:27:10,000
So that was a little piece in helping us to close our budget gap.

2128
03:27:13,263 --> 03:27:13,483
Great.

2129
03:27:13,523 --> 03:27:13,803
Thank you.

2130
03:27:13,823 --> 03:27:16,445
Do we have any more questions for our team from Memphis Public Schools?

2131
03:27:20,229 --> 03:27:22,711
Chief of Staff seems to want to speak.

2132
03:27:27,662 --> 03:27:29,664
I get the unpopular job most of the time.

2133
03:27:29,684 --> 03:27:44,118
I want to start off by saying that I have a lot of respect for my peers here today and I know that my peers are doing everything that they can for the schools and the children and it's incredibly hard to come up here and

2134
03:27:45,359 --> 03:27:49,462
present a different perspective with regard to the base budget.

2135
03:27:51,144 --> 03:27:57,609
My peers know the position of the school, of the city on this matter, and so none of this is gonna come to them as a surprise.

2136
03:28:02,092 --> 03:28:12,320
The higher figure that's being, I think it's important to start off on, before I dive deep into base budget details, to say that this is fairly complicated.

2137
03:28:16,122 --> 03:28:17,863
not something I would expect.

2138
03:28:17,883 --> 03:28:26,027
I personally, if I was seated in your positions, to be candid with you, my learning system would not allow me to digest this this evening.

2139
03:28:27,208 --> 03:28:31,150
But I'm going to go through this and I'm going to state what I feel needs to be stated.

2140
03:28:33,312 --> 03:28:34,773
And I'm happy to answer any questions.

2141
03:28:34,793 --> 03:28:39,697
I'm also happy to provide this written down if that's helpful.

2142
03:28:40,338 --> 03:28:46,723
I hope, I hope maybe part of it doesn't even matter because I think we're all just headed towards the same direction.

2143
03:28:46,763 --> 03:28:52,689
But I, it's important to outline the differences in perspective in terms of the base budget here because

2144
03:28:54,240 --> 03:29:10,573
These types of things are going to then, if, if unaddressed by myself, for instance, they are gonna go down the road and be assumed that, for instance, the, the city's finance team on, on the municipal side and the city administration agree that this is a part of the base budget when we don't believe that that's accurate.

2145
03:29:14,417 --> 03:29:21,462
The, the higher figure that's being discussed is effectively incorporating the FY 26 general fund appropriation of $85,400,000.

2146
03:29:23,845 --> 03:29:34,743
$90,000 and then adding funds that were carried into Fiscal 26 from 25 through the Stabilization Fund, effectively treating those funds as part of the ongoing base.

2147
03:29:36,603 --> 03:29:41,704
From our perspective, that approach doesn't align with the original intent or budgeting logic, in my opinion.

2148
03:29:42,985 --> 03:29:45,065
As we understand it, the progression is as follows.

2149
03:29:45,125 --> 03:29:47,266
The fiscal 25 budget was $76 million.

2150
03:29:48,726 --> 03:29:52,267
Question seven was $3 million approved by the voters, this council, of course.

2151
03:29:52,967 --> 03:29:55,708
Question eight, $4 million approved by this council and the voters.

2152
03:29:56,428 --> 03:29:58,569
The total fiscal 25 appropriation was $83 million.

2153
03:30:00,617 --> 03:30:10,263
For fiscal 26, the $83 million total was increased by 3%, inclusive of the $7 million override, resulting in a general fund appropriation of $85,490,000.

2154
03:30:12,964 --> 03:30:22,350
Separately, as has been discussed tonight, the $2.185 million from question eight was placed into a stabilization fund with the following planned use schedule.

2155
03:30:23,732 --> 03:30:24,353
Fiscal 26, $1.85 million.

2156
03:30:24,393 --> 03:30:24,613
Fiscal 27, $750,000.

2157
03:30:24,713 --> 03:30:24,894
Fiscal 28, $350,000.

2158
03:30:34,434 --> 03:30:38,977
For fiscal 27, applying a 2.76 increase to the fiscal 26 base of $85,490,000 yields $87,850, 887 million, I don't know what I've been saying to be honest with you, I think I'm losing it here.

2159
03:30:38,997 --> 03:30:42,979
$87,850,000 consistent with the city's finance director's communication back in February of 2026 to the school department.

2160
03:31:06,472 --> 03:31:08,253
Again, we're referring now to Fiscal 27.

2161
03:31:08,694 --> 03:31:13,477
The agreed upon use of the Stabilization Fund in Fiscal 27 was $750,000.

2162
03:31:14,457 --> 03:31:20,281
Reframing these amounts, and this is probably the key to focus on because that was just a lot of numbers.

2163
03:31:21,082 --> 03:31:32,830
Reframing these amounts in a way that incorporates Stabilization Fund into the base effectively suggests that the school would receive not only the $7 million in the override, but also another $2.185 million.

2164
03:31:36,938 --> 03:31:39,181
added permanently to the base by Fiscal 28.

2165
03:31:40,202 --> 03:31:44,547
That $2.185 million was already part of the original Question No.

2166
03:31:44,807 --> 03:31:55,579
8 funding in Fiscal 25 and was intended to only be phased forward to avoid absorption into free cash, not to permanently increase the baseline budget.

2167
03:31:57,682 --> 03:32:07,048
Treating those same dollars as both a temporary bridge across fiscal years and a permanent addition to the base budget results in counting the same funds twice in different ways.

2168
03:32:08,089 --> 03:32:16,275
The outcome materially changes the agreed upon financial framework and produces a higher ongoing obligation than was originally contemplated.

2169
03:32:17,295 --> 03:32:22,299
Another way to frame the concern is to say that the voters did not approve a $9.185 million override.

2170
03:32:25,798 --> 03:32:35,602
Another, yet another way to say it is by looking at the overall trajectory, the FY24 school general fund budget was $71 million roughly.

2171
03:32:35,622 --> 03:32:37,003
It was just over $71 million.

2172
03:32:37,823 --> 03:32:43,926
And the current interpretation points towards a FY27 requirement on the order of $90 million.

2173
03:32:45,467 --> 03:32:52,470
That scale increase over a short period further underscores the extent to which this approach departs from the original financial plan.

2174
03:32:54,891 --> 03:33:03,117
Again, I understand that we're all vying for the same dollars and the schools is just doing that for the best interest of the community and I support that.

2175
03:33:03,398 --> 03:33:04,558
I think the mayor supports that.

2176
03:33:04,579 --> 03:33:05,419
Everyone supports that.

2177
03:33:05,459 --> 03:33:06,520
I know you all support that.

2178
03:33:07,721 --> 03:33:21,071
But I just can't not indicate that there is a very real and concerning point with regard to treating the $2.185 million as part of the base budget because it's not.

2179
03:33:21,872 --> 03:33:22,092
Thank you.

2180
03:33:27,062 --> 03:33:28,062
Thank you.

2181
03:33:30,823 --> 03:33:33,263
Is there anything you guys wanna say about that?

2182
03:33:33,363 --> 03:33:37,924
Yeah, I think on this point we agree to disagree.

2183
03:33:39,164 --> 03:33:51,266
You know, our position is that initially we did receive a 4 million dollars from question 8 in our FY25 budget and we reduced that amount by 2.1.

2184
03:33:52,646 --> 03:33:55,407
So we technically we did not get

2185
03:33:56,993 --> 03:34:02,274
$4 million added to our budget at the end of the day.

2186
03:34:02,314 --> 03:34:23,320
And we did indicate in the FY 26 budget if we go back to those slides and we were having a very similar discussion about a budget gap, we indicated that we would use a million eighty-five to close the gap.

2187
03:34:26,950 --> 03:34:31,891
adding that money to our budget in order to help close the gap.

2188
03:34:33,112 --> 03:34:55,238
The other thing was if you remember the $3 million in question 7, a large amount of that was given to us in our appropriation kind of pre-funded, you know, without knowing how that,

2189
03:34:57,025 --> 03:35:05,529
override would pass, so the city did have a plan to fund that, you know, in the event the override didn't pass.

2190
03:35:05,629 --> 03:35:16,615
But when the override did pass, the city was retained, I want to say it was about $1.7 million.

2191
03:35:17,095 --> 03:35:16,615
1.75.

2192
03:35:17,115 --> 03:35:25,880
1.75 to kind of make them whole for the money they had already given us.

2193
03:35:27,467 --> 03:35:34,132
The additional 1.2 or so was added to our budget in the supplemental.

2194
03:35:34,732 --> 03:35:47,821
So, you know, I think at the end of the day, we, it's still a $2 million budget gap no matter how you slice or dice it.

2195
03:35:49,562 --> 03:35:52,905
We do not believe we're spending

2196
03:35:56,173 --> 03:36:05,019
9.8, 9 million, 9.1 million dollars from override amount of 7 million.

2197
03:36:06,459 --> 03:36:15,164
That's not something we can agree to but we are using

2198
03:36:16,949 --> 03:36:37,386
$2.1 million that we turned back in FY25 in order to spend it over the next three years and that part of the reason of doing that was to manage the impact of kind of unwinding from that stabilization fund.

2199
03:36:37,885 --> 03:36:51,415
But the other aspect of it was it follows the three-year contract that we have with the teacher's union and that's, you know, what the money was voted on in order to

2200
03:36:52,885 --> 03:37:00,090
meet the requirements of the schedule and improve the salaries of teachers and paraprofessionals, so.

2201
03:37:00,790 --> 03:37:06,594
And just if we want the numbers, it did bring back, we cut 14 full-time positions at that time.

2202
03:37:07,134 --> 03:37:12,218
And when the override was successful, we were able to reinstate those 14 positions.

2203
03:37:12,238 --> 03:37:15,480
All right.

2204
03:37:17,081 --> 03:37:21,544
Yeah, I mean, I kind of, not to add a third perspective to the whole situation,

2205
03:37:22,269 --> 03:37:41,553
But, you know, my understanding was that these funds were essentially serving as a ramp for the city to have general fund increases greater than 2.75% per year.

2206
03:37:42,074 --> 03:37:48,035
Understanding that the schools would need that and these funds were a ramp so that the city budget could sustain that.

2207
03:37:49,083 --> 03:38:00,809
And that's why I was considering a part of the base and just reading from the letter where we established the, I mean, I could see it being interpreted differently than I'm interpreting it, but this is June 18th, 2025 from the mayor.

2208
03:38:01,590 --> 03:38:05,652
Establish and transfer funds to Medford Public Schools special purpose override stabilization funds.

2209
03:38:05,712 --> 03:38:14,056
It concludes, by taking this action, we will have a source of funding available to supplement the Medford Public Schools annual operating budget in the upcoming fiscal year or future fiscal year.

2210
03:38:15,350 --> 03:38:25,561
It specifically says annual operating budget which means recurring expenditures not one time expenses and therefore needs to be planned for to be maintained going forward.

2211
03:38:26,382 --> 03:38:31,828
So that's like what we voted on the letter to establish the stabilization fund from the mayor.

2212
03:38:34,798 --> 03:38:47,665
So I agree with the chief of staff it's not that the overrides 9.1 million but I also agree with you guys that it's to supplement the annual operating budget in the upcoming fiscal year and in future fiscal years which is what the mayor wrote to us when we approved the fund.

2213
03:38:48,165 --> 03:38:49,906
So thank you.

2214
03:38:50,006 --> 03:38:50,767
Councillor Callahan.

2215
03:38:52,852 --> 03:39:05,480
I was just going to say that this is one reason why it's not advised for cities and towns to use free cash or stabilization funds for operating expenses because here we are and nobody knows, right?

2216
03:39:06,040 --> 03:39:14,105
Wow, gosh, we used millions of dollars of essentially savings for operating expenses and now we don't know.

2217
03:39:14,385 --> 03:39:15,726
We don't know what the voters wanted.

2218
03:39:16,867 --> 03:39:18,308
So hopefully we will not be doing that again.

2219
03:39:19,955 --> 03:39:31,277
Well, as Chief of Staff said, it was designed to prevent that money from going to free cash and preserve it for what the voters intended with that money.

2220
03:39:34,338 --> 03:39:34,478
Right.

2221
03:39:34,558 --> 03:39:45,380
And I think if it seemed to me from the letter from the mayor from last year that we were all in agreement that we know that the schools need more than 2.75 percent per year above the

2222
03:39:46,187 --> 03:39:52,172
even with the override figure included, and that this was a way to mitigate that ramp up.

2223
03:39:52,632 --> 03:40:00,859
You know, the city would have to do a little bit less in fiscal 26, you know, than they otherwise would have a little bit more in 27, a little bit more in 28.

2224
03:40:01,739 --> 03:40:04,201
And then in 29, it would be addressed.

2225
03:40:04,301 --> 03:40:11,467
But it seems like where we were in agreement in the letter being submitted to us last year, we're not in agreement anymore.

2226
03:40:14,077 --> 03:40:19,340
Do we have any further questions for the school leadership team?

2227
03:40:24,442 --> 03:40:25,383
All right, thank you.

2228
03:40:25,403 --> 03:40:26,003
Thank you.

2229
03:40:26,023 --> 03:40:26,203
All right.

2230
03:40:27,904 --> 03:40:28,785
Thank you all very much.

2231
03:40:28,965 --> 03:40:30,866
DPW, we have Tim McGivern.

2232
03:40:30,906 --> 03:40:33,187
We'll do general fund, then we'll do enterprise fund.

2233
03:40:33,587 --> 03:40:39,430
And I'll take it in, I think the order that it's in the packet, Tim.

2234
03:40:40,551 --> 03:40:42,112
So we can start with highway.

2235
03:40:43,324 --> 03:40:46,548
Sure, good evening President Behrs and council members.

2236
03:40:50,934 --> 03:40:53,258
I had a late cup of coffee, so I'm good.

2237
03:40:55,788 --> 03:41:01,713
But I have just a small presentation to make, just reading off some of the facts from last year.

2238
03:41:02,473 --> 03:41:04,635
And then we can dive into questions.

2239
03:41:05,015 --> 03:41:05,296
Great.

2240
03:41:05,816 --> 03:41:10,039
So as many of you know, DPW is comprised of seven divisions.

2241
03:41:11,260 --> 03:41:17,425
And those are engineering, fleet, water and sewer, highway, forestry, parks, and cemetery.

2242
03:41:18,526 --> 03:41:23,090
We operate with general fund money as well as water and sewer enterprise and perpetual care funds.

2243
03:41:24,088 --> 03:41:25,869
Our budget this year is about $48 million.

2244
03:41:26,109 --> 03:41:29,911
A lot of that is water, buying water for the city.

2245
03:41:31,852 --> 03:41:36,494
So lots of great stuff happened over the past year or so.

2246
03:41:36,514 --> 03:41:46,278
As a lot of you know, and we talked a little bit about earlier, we have an urban forest management plan now that was paid for by the state through an MVP grant.

2247
03:41:47,066 --> 03:41:50,952
That included a tree inventory, which is really exciting because we didn't have that before.

2248
03:41:51,012 --> 03:41:54,016
So now we have a GIS-based tree inventory, which is wonderful.

2249
03:41:57,016 --> 03:42:06,159
And another big thing that we've been working on, that I think most of you know about as well, is transitioning our waste contracts into a more modern waste system.

2250
03:42:07,600 --> 03:42:11,741
So that's just some big sort of administrative accomplishments.

2251
03:42:12,181 --> 03:42:14,302
The engineering division has been up to a lot.

2252
03:42:14,342 --> 03:42:16,383
There's five new staff members in engineering.

2253
03:42:17,883 --> 03:42:20,024
Hopefully, you've seen lots of improvements going on.

2254
03:42:20,064 --> 03:42:24,066
A big one was the traffic signal improvements at Spring Street and Central, for example.

2255
03:42:25,671 --> 03:42:32,485
We basically completed resurfacing of six streets, about 5,650 feet, about 11,000 feet of sidewalk reconstruction.

2256
03:42:38,229 --> 03:42:52,760
We did 7,700 feet of water main, 4,600 feet of sewer main, and we are rapidly removing the lead from the service lines, feeding the homes and businesses here in Medford.

2257
03:42:53,280 --> 03:42:54,781
We resolved 857 of those, which is a large amount.

2258
03:43:04,848 --> 03:43:13,034
Fleet maintenance, we take care of 240 city vehicles, including 27 fire apparatus, 51 police vehicles, and 20 pieces of heavy equipment.

2259
03:43:15,035 --> 03:43:25,802
In the water and sewer division, we take care of 15,083 water services, and those come off of 144 miles of distribution pipe.

2260
03:43:26,703 --> 03:43:31,366
And one of the big things that we accomplished in water this year is finished a citywide meter swap.

2261
03:43:31,426 --> 03:43:34,068
We only have a few left, so that was a very large accomplishment.

2262
03:43:35,205 --> 03:43:41,247
And we fixed 66 water service leaks and 67 water main breaks.

2263
03:43:41,968 --> 03:43:44,028
I'll talk a little bit more about that in a minute.

2264
03:43:45,509 --> 03:43:52,151
Highway, so we maintain 95 miles of public roads and about 29 miles of private roadways.

2265
03:43:52,531 --> 03:43:53,892
Private roadways have limited service.

2266
03:43:55,578 --> 03:44:01,603
We placed about 780 tons of asphalt this past year, repaired 110 structures.

2267
03:44:02,323 --> 03:44:05,186
We painted 375,000 feet of traffic lines.

2268
03:44:06,207 --> 03:44:10,650
And we have, it's not new anymore, but we've had paving equipment for the last couple of years.

2269
03:44:10,910 --> 03:44:16,815
And last season, we did 11 paving spots, which is much larger than a patch.

2270
03:44:16,875 --> 03:44:18,677
We paved a stretch of road, basically.

2271
03:44:18,697 --> 03:44:20,298
And that was about 590 tons of asphalt.

2272
03:44:23,159 --> 03:44:33,209
The forestry division is something that I looked at over the course of the last year with the urban forest management plan.

2273
03:44:33,229 --> 03:44:40,235
It helps me as the manager of the DPW to know what we're up against and what we need to do to service those assets.

2274
03:44:40,696 --> 03:44:42,758
So that was really important for the DPW.

2275
03:44:44,078 --> 03:44:46,619
The parks division, we have a lot of parks in Medford.

2276
03:44:47,220 --> 03:44:58,946
We have 16 major parks, 7 passive parks, and 14 playgrounds, 9 baseball fields, 7 softball fields, 4 soccer fields, 13 basketball courts, 9 tennis courts, and a pickleball court.

2277
03:45:00,026 --> 03:45:08,591
And this year we are refinishing or refurbishing, however you'd like to call it, Playstead Park tennis courts, which is a very, very popular set of tennis courts here in the city.

2278
03:45:12,758 --> 03:45:17,020
Goals for next year, they kind of build off of goals from last year.

2279
03:45:17,040 --> 03:45:19,782
We want to improve our asphalt operations.

2280
03:45:21,143 --> 03:45:25,125
We want to have two to three highway division trainings for asphalt knowledge and skills.

2281
03:45:25,825 --> 03:45:27,987
We plan on upgrading our milling equipment.

2282
03:45:29,788 --> 03:45:39,554
And we are shooting for weekly deployment of our paving equipment this season, which goes through November.

2283
03:45:40,996 --> 03:45:51,162
Another goal is to improve our concrete operations, have two to three highway division trainings for concrete knowledge and skills, and weekly deployment of concrete spot repair crew.

2284
03:45:53,263 --> 03:45:57,706
Another goal is to establish protocols for tree inventory updates.

2285
03:45:57,846 --> 03:45:58,907
We're already working on that.

2286
03:45:58,987 --> 03:46:03,910
It's a collaboration between the GIS and engineering division and the forestry division.

2287
03:46:05,209 --> 03:46:11,356
The goal is to have an effective GIS-based tree database that can be used effectively for asset management.

2288
03:46:12,357 --> 03:46:17,623
Another goal is to have 100% of the lead services removed out of the ground by 2032.

2289
03:46:17,944 --> 03:46:22,669
That goal is going to remain until then.

2290
03:46:24,272 --> 03:46:31,194
Then we have a lot of capital projects going on at the cemetery, so we have a goal to make some progress on those projects.

2291
03:46:31,594 --> 03:46:34,555
We have an expansion design going on.

2292
03:46:35,095 --> 03:46:38,416
We have a soil removal project that is almost done.

2293
03:46:38,436 --> 03:46:45,258
I'm hoping this is the last year of doing that, and then we'll have just regular operational removals after that.

2294
03:46:45,478 --> 03:46:46,638
Piles looking good, Tim.

2295
03:46:47,158 --> 03:46:47,859
The piles looking good?

2296
03:46:47,879 --> 03:46:48,039
Yeah.

2297
03:46:48,159 --> 03:46:48,940
Yeah, it's getting down there.

2298
03:46:49,060 --> 03:46:49,260
Yeah.

2299
03:46:49,420 --> 03:46:52,082
Yeah, the weeds growing on top, though, look kind of big.

2300
03:46:52,122 --> 03:46:53,163
They almost look like trees, so.

2301
03:46:55,204 --> 03:47:03,211
Anyway, you know, and the roads up there are horrible, so we have a project there that we're trying to make some progress on, and buildings as well.

2302
03:47:03,251 --> 03:47:05,332
We have two buildings that are in rough shape.

2303
03:47:05,713 --> 03:47:14,740
We have estimates for preserving those buildings that are quite high, and then I'm actually working on doing a comparison of what a new building might look like in cost.

2304
03:47:16,002 --> 03:47:19,025
to compare, so I'd like to make some progress on those.

2305
03:47:20,005 --> 03:47:34,519
And then we are continuing to work on asset management transition to field devices, so the goals right now, we have water set up, but really to move on to highway engineering and forestry, especially for the trees as we talked about.

2306
03:47:36,755 --> 03:47:42,918
Just to get ahead a couple of questions, you know, some of the concerns that I have with this particular budget is material costs.

2307
03:47:43,018 --> 03:47:43,898
Those go up every year.

2308
03:47:44,759 --> 03:47:48,600
So, you know, really our DPW budget, even if we do a level budget, it is cut.

2309
03:47:49,341 --> 03:47:53,963
Even if it's level across the boards because material costs go up, contract costs go up as well.

2310
03:47:54,543 --> 03:47:58,225
Fuel costs is a concern I have this year in particular because it's so variable.

2311
03:47:58,245 --> 03:47:59,886
We don't know what's going to happen with fuel right now.

2312
03:47:59,946 --> 03:48:04,928
So we kind of did our best and did some shock analysis to see what our budget could handle.

2313
03:48:05,368 --> 03:48:09,910
And it should be able to handle reasonable increases in fuel.

2314
03:48:11,211 --> 03:48:20,895
And then things that are challenging and are coming is more regulation and more enforcement of those regulations.

2315
03:48:21,135 --> 03:48:22,896
We're seeing more ADA activity.

2316
03:48:25,337 --> 03:48:39,447
more requests for GIS services, you know, we're seeing a lot of activity from the state and local, the state and federal level for water regulations, keeping our water clean, things like that.

2317
03:48:40,408 --> 03:48:44,331
And then also deteriorating assets, which I talk about a lot with this group.

2318
03:48:45,052 --> 03:48:49,855
You know, we have an old water system, we have old roads, and they all happen to be failing now.

2319
03:48:50,355 --> 03:48:52,297
They're long failures, so, you know,

2320
03:48:52,840 --> 03:49:00,203
over the next, for water, probably over the next 20 years, 15 to 20 years, we really should have everything replaced by then.

2321
03:49:00,443 --> 03:49:15,389
And then roads as well, we're maintaining a steady condition index, but we're talking with the mayor on what the capital plan should look like to start to tick up on our index, which is great.

2322
03:49:16,669 --> 03:49:20,171
And then I'm always trying to right size the department and

2323
03:49:21,973 --> 03:49:29,198
I've worked on kind of each division, one division per year, and we just got finished looking at forestry.

2324
03:49:29,838 --> 03:49:39,824
You talked a little bit about what a right size of forestry might look like, so we know that information, so we have something to work towards over time, and then I see

2325
03:49:41,345 --> 03:49:46,288
Retaining and hiring mechanics is a significant issue coming, too.

2326
03:49:46,828 --> 03:49:51,930
The private industry pays mechanics a lot better than here on the public side.

2327
03:49:52,591 --> 03:49:56,353
So we've been trying to hire mechanics for going on a year.

2328
03:49:56,713 --> 03:50:04,077
And unfortunately, it's not one of those jobs where if we increase the salary, we're going to attract more people, because we just won't be able to compete with $50, $60 an hour out there.

2329
03:50:07,354 --> 03:50:10,445
you know, private fleets are giving out.

2330
03:50:17,385 --> 03:50:21,108
And then just a little bit about the override and what we're doing there.

2331
03:50:21,409 --> 03:50:28,535
So we have three new employees, and I would say now we're at a normal sort of opening level.

2332
03:50:29,135 --> 03:50:34,260
We do have a handful of openings, but we've filled the highway rolls.

2333
03:50:34,941 --> 03:50:38,183
We bought a new hotbox, so we have two pothole crews now.

2334
03:50:38,824 --> 03:50:41,787
Actually, that second hotbox is going to be deployed next week.

2335
03:50:44,226 --> 03:50:47,148
And then we're planning on upgrading our milling machine.

2336
03:50:47,548 --> 03:50:51,591
And as I talked about, we're deploying our paver more and more.

2337
03:50:51,611 --> 03:50:56,914
So we're going to continue to do that to keep our condition index high, or as high as we can.

2338
03:50:58,275 --> 03:51:03,398
And then you notice some adds in the budget, some decreases, too, to right-size things.

2339
03:51:03,418 --> 03:51:09,242
But we need more software, CitizenServe, other things.

2340
03:51:11,601 --> 03:51:14,382
Our fleet, the fleet is getting older.

2341
03:51:14,603 --> 03:51:21,286
We're replacing vehicles, but we seem to have a little bit more in fleet costs each year.

2342
03:51:21,446 --> 03:51:22,446
So you'll see some of that.

2343
03:51:24,087 --> 03:51:26,628
Tree warden is another tick up.

2344
03:51:26,868 --> 03:51:28,869
We're paying that position more now.

2345
03:51:29,430 --> 03:51:30,990
So I think you saw that the other night.

2346
03:51:33,772 --> 03:51:36,613
And solid waste has an uptick as well.

2347
03:51:38,264 --> 03:51:42,487
And then water main breaks as well as wholesale water increases.

2348
03:51:42,807 --> 03:51:45,009
So those are kind of the big increases that we saw this year.

2349
03:51:46,050 --> 03:51:46,570
Thank you very much.

2350
03:51:47,631 --> 03:51:48,091
Thank you.

2351
03:51:48,111 --> 03:51:49,012
Vice President Lazaro.

2352
03:51:51,374 --> 03:51:52,655
Thank you for the presentation.

2353
03:51:53,956 --> 03:52:02,142
Could you just help me understand in the parks budget it says food for the inmates and I don't see who pays.

2354
03:52:03,143 --> 03:52:03,704
So who.

2355
03:52:04,244 --> 03:52:04,864
Can you explain.

2356
03:52:06,146 --> 03:52:06,306
Yes.

2357
03:52:07,856 --> 03:52:18,420
So we have a partnership with the state correctional facility, and we basically have inmates that will do work on our islands.

2358
03:52:19,421 --> 03:52:21,261
Governor's Avenue is a good example.

2359
03:52:21,301 --> 03:52:24,663
They trim all the weeds up against the wall a couple times a year.

2360
03:52:25,203 --> 03:52:27,844
So the deal is that we provide them lunch.

2361
03:52:28,424 --> 03:52:28,884
We feed them.

2362
03:52:29,125 --> 03:52:29,645
That's the deal.

2363
03:52:30,845 --> 03:52:31,806
And they come in and do some work.

2364
03:52:31,826 --> 03:52:32,806
Do you know how much they get paid?

2365
03:52:34,467 --> 03:52:34,907
They don't get paid.

2366
03:52:35,898 --> 03:52:36,438
that we feed them.

2367
03:52:36,658 --> 03:52:37,159
I hate that.

2368
03:52:38,379 --> 03:52:39,880
I know it's not anything I can do.

2369
03:52:41,361 --> 03:52:42,442
I hate that so much.

2370
03:52:43,202 --> 03:52:47,544
It is part of their rehabilitation and their community service.

2371
03:52:48,265 --> 03:52:49,045
OK.

2372
03:52:49,345 --> 03:52:50,166
It's community service?

2373
03:52:50,546 --> 03:52:52,467
I think it counts as community service for them, I believe.

2374
03:52:54,428 --> 03:52:55,949
They want to be good standing as prisoners.

2375
03:52:57,170 --> 03:52:59,771
We have great success with them.

2376
03:52:59,811 --> 03:53:00,712
No, I'm sure they're wonderful.

2377
03:53:00,932 --> 03:53:02,933
The thing that I hate is that they're not

2378
03:53:04,198 --> 03:53:12,914
being paid money, but if it's for community service, but it says inmates, so I'm confused.

2379
03:53:17,647 --> 03:53:18,147
I'm confused.

2380
03:53:18,607 --> 03:53:25,171
Also the actuals in the parks budget in general seem really low in a few places.

2381
03:53:25,311 --> 03:53:27,292
Is it where they just know it's 527.

2382
03:53:28,232 --> 03:53:28,852
It doesn't really matter.

2383
03:53:28,872 --> 03:53:31,734
It seems like the actuals are all over the place in a lot of these budgets.

2384
03:53:33,755 --> 03:53:42,119
And I did notice that in the highway budget the I think that was just because this year we had an insane amount of snow but it was private contractors was really high.

2385
03:53:42,619 --> 03:53:42,919
Is that why.

2386
03:53:44,906 --> 03:53:47,447
If it was the snow and ice contract line, then yeah.

2387
03:53:47,607 --> 03:53:48,968
It just said private contractors.

2388
03:53:49,028 --> 03:53:49,348
Hold on.

2389
03:53:51,168 --> 03:53:53,369
There's a lot of papers for your department.

2390
03:53:55,269 --> 03:53:55,489
Yes.

2391
03:53:56,910 --> 03:54:06,213
Yeah, it was in highway, and it's highlighted, and it says private contractors.

2392
03:54:06,233 --> 03:54:08,233
46,000 is budgeted, $238,212 is in actuals.

2393
03:54:14,320 --> 03:54:17,361
And then $46,000 is proposed budget for next year.

2394
03:54:18,701 --> 03:54:20,862
Any idea why it would be like that?

2395
03:54:25,143 --> 03:54:26,644
There are two lines.

2396
03:54:26,744 --> 03:54:31,645
One says private contractors, the other says snow and ice materials, which is also astronomically high.

2397
03:54:32,685 --> 03:54:37,427
That whole highlighted section on highway is kind of all over the place.

2398
03:54:38,982 --> 03:54:40,523
Does it even out if you add it all up?

2399
03:54:40,603 --> 03:54:42,744
It might be snow and ice.

2400
03:54:43,244 --> 03:54:44,705
Well, they're probably both snow and ice.

2401
03:54:44,785 --> 03:54:47,167
It's line items 423-5241 to 423-5530.

2402
03:54:47,567 --> 03:54:49,588
Oh, I see it.

2403
03:54:49,768 --> 03:54:50,368
Yeah.

2404
03:54:50,508 --> 03:54:51,089
Yeah.

2405
03:54:51,329 --> 03:54:52,990
That's snow and ice contractors.

2406
03:54:53,070 --> 03:54:55,471
So we have actuals from those two large storms.

2407
03:54:55,671 --> 03:54:55,971
Yeah.

2408
03:54:56,192 --> 03:54:59,774
And then... It's materials and it's contractors.

2409
03:55:00,234 --> 03:55:04,776
Sometimes, last year I think we had, we zeroed out all the snow and ice lines.

2410
03:55:05,277 --> 03:55:06,557
This year it doesn't look like we are.

2411
03:55:06,577 --> 03:55:07,698
There's some, you know,

2412
03:55:08,185 --> 03:55:09,205
nominal amount in there.

2413
03:55:11,986 --> 03:55:12,587
Sorry, wait.

2414
03:55:14,067 --> 03:55:15,427
How do you mean you zeroed it all out?

2415
03:55:16,268 --> 03:55:19,509
So last year when we did the budget, it's been different each year.

2416
03:55:19,549 --> 03:55:24,811
The last few years, our proposed budget just would have zero in those lines.

2417
03:55:26,031 --> 03:55:26,271
Why?

2418
03:55:26,771 --> 03:55:33,114
Because snow and ice can go into deficit, and it's an unforecasted or non-forecasted expense.

2419
03:55:33,594 --> 03:55:34,374
That's why it's highlighted.

2420
03:55:35,739 --> 03:55:38,741
It's highlighted because I think it was changed, I think.

2421
03:55:38,761 --> 03:55:40,742
So now it's not going to be zeroed out?

2422
03:55:40,762 --> 03:55:45,305
It's highlighted because it's snow and ice, I think.

2423
03:55:45,685 --> 03:55:47,386
The whole section is highlighted as snow and ice.

2424
03:55:47,406 --> 03:55:49,948
All of those highlighted items are the snow and ice line items.

2425
03:55:50,148 --> 03:55:50,568
OK.

2426
03:55:51,369 --> 03:56:01,335
I guess my question here is those actuals don't seem to match the budget for either year.

2427
03:56:04,004 --> 03:56:04,804
No, and they won't.

2428
03:56:05,145 --> 03:56:05,825
We would expect them not to.

2429
03:56:05,845 --> 03:56:06,245
And they won't ever?

2430
03:56:06,785 --> 03:56:09,366
So what's the point of having a budget?

2431
03:56:12,628 --> 03:56:19,411
It's lines that we track, lines that we use for expenses in the accounting software and NPOs.

2432
03:56:19,431 --> 03:56:21,312
Yeah, so those are the lines we use.

2433
03:56:21,412 --> 03:56:22,672
Just silly little games, OK.

2434
03:56:22,772 --> 03:56:25,994
Yeah, and there's no money in those lines until we spend the money.

2435
03:56:26,154 --> 03:56:28,495
And I don't know the mechanics behind how that happens.

2436
03:56:29,535 --> 03:56:31,356
OK, there's no money in the lines until you spend it.

2437
03:56:31,476 --> 03:56:33,177
So it gets put in as needed.

2438
03:56:34,497 --> 03:56:36,619
Well, it's an emergency response.

2439
03:56:36,879 --> 03:56:37,159
Got it.

2440
03:56:37,720 --> 03:56:40,242
So, um, and you know, it looks like maybe she has more to say.

2441
03:56:43,886 --> 03:56:57,555
Just to say, thank you for the opportunity, just to say that it's common with cities and towns to kind of keep a level budget with snow and ice because of the unprecedented changes that happen year after year.

2442
03:56:58,096 --> 03:57:04,020
It is one of the only budgets that we can spend into deficit under state statutes with the understanding that

2443
03:57:04,720 --> 03:57:08,441
You know, we can't predict snow and ice each year.

2444
03:57:08,561 --> 03:57:11,022
We can't possibly anticipate that amount.

2445
03:57:11,642 --> 03:57:18,524
Also, and I need to check my facts on this, but my recollection is that if we do increase it, we can't decrease it in subsequent years.

2446
03:57:18,604 --> 03:57:24,586
